maze_dataset.tokenization

turning a maze into text

  • MazeTokenizerModular is the new recommended way to do this as of 1.0.0
  • legacy TokenizationMode enum and MazeTokenizer class for supporting existing code
  • a whole lot of helper classes and functions
View on GitHub 

 1"""turning a maze into text
 2
 3- `MazeTokenizerModular` is the new recommended way to do this as of 1.0.0
 4- legacy `TokenizationMode` enum and `MazeTokenizer` class for supporting existing code
 5- a whole lot of helper classes and functions
 6
 7"""

class TokenizationMode(enum.Enum):
View on GitHub 
71class TokenizationMode(Enum):
72	"""legacy tokenization modes
73
74	> [!CAUTION]
75	> Legacy mode of tokenization. will still be around in future releases, but is no longer recommended for use.
76	> Use `MazeTokenizerModular` instead.
77
78	# Abbreviations:
79	- `AOTP`: Ajacency list, Origin, Target, Path
80	- `UT`: Unique Token (for each coordiate)
81	- `CTT`: Coordinate Tuple Tokens (each coordinate is tokenized as a tuple of integers)
82
83	# Modes:
84	- `AOTP_UT_rasterized`: the "classic" mode: assigning tokens to each coordinate is done via rasterization
85		example: for a 3x3 maze, token order is `(0,0), (0,1), (0,2), (1,0), (1,1), (1,2), (2,0), (2,1), (2,2)`
86	- `AOTP_UT_uniform`: new mode, where a 3x3 tokenization scheme and 5x5 tokenizations scheme are compatible
87		uses `corner_first_ndindex` function to order the tokens
88	- `AOTP_CTT_indexed`: each coordinate is a tuple of integers
89	"""
90
91	AOTP_UT_rasterized = "AOTP_UT_rasterized"
92	AOTP_UT_uniform = "AOTP_UT_uniform"
93	AOTP_CTT_indexed = "AOTP_CTT_indexed"
94
95	def to_legacy_tokenizer(self, max_grid_size: int | None = None) -> "MazeTokenizer":
96		"convert the mode to a legacy `MazeTokenizer` object given a `max_grid_size`"
97		return MazeTokenizer(tokenization_mode=self, max_grid_size=max_grid_size)

legacy tokenization modes

Caution

Legacy mode of tokenization. will still be around in future releases, but is no longer recommended for use. Use MazeTokenizerModular instead.

Abbreviations:

  • AOTP: Ajacency list, Origin, Target, Path
  • UT: Unique Token (for each coordiate)
  • CTT: Coordinate Tuple Tokens (each coordinate is tokenized as a tuple of integers)

Modes:

  • AOTP_UT_rasterized: the "classic" mode: assigning tokens to each coordinate is done via rasterization example: for a 3x3 maze, token order is (0,0), (0,1), (0,2), (1,0), (1,1), (1,2), (2,0), (2,1), (2,2)
  • AOTP_UT_uniform: new mode, where a 3x3 tokenization scheme and 5x5 tokenizations scheme are compatible uses corner_first_ndindex function to order the tokens
  • AOTP_CTT_indexed: each coordinate is a tuple of integers
AOTP_UT_rasterized = <TokenizationMode.AOTP_UT_rasterized: 'AOTP_UT_rasterized'>
AOTP_UT_uniform = <TokenizationMode.AOTP_UT_uniform: 'AOTP_UT_uniform'>
AOTP_CTT_indexed = <TokenizationMode.AOTP_CTT_indexed: 'AOTP_CTT_indexed'>

class _TokenizerElement(muutils.json_serialize.serializable_dataclass.SerializableDataclass, abc.ABC):
View on GitHub 
528@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
529class _TokenizerElement(SerializableDataclass, abc.ABC):
530	"""Superclass for tokenizer elements.
531
532	Subclasses contain modular functionality for maze tokenization.
533
534	# Development
535	> [!TIP]
536	> Due to the functionality of `get_all_tokenizers()`, `_TokenizerElement` subclasses
537	> may only contain fields of type `utils.FiniteValued`.
538	> Implementing a subclass with an `int` or `float`-typed field, for example, is not supported.
539	> In the event that adding such fields is deemed necessary, `get_all_tokenizers()` must be updated.
540
541	"""
542
543	# TYPING: type hint `v` more specifically
544	@staticmethod
545	def _stringify(k: str, v: Any) -> str:  # noqa: ANN401
546		if isinstance(v, bool):
547			return f"{k}={str(v)[0]}"
548		if isinstance(v, _TokenizerElement):
549			return v.name
550		if isinstance(v, tuple):
551			return f"{k}={''.join(['(', *[str(x) + ', ' for x in v], ')'])}"
552		else:
553			return f"{k}={v}"
554
555	@property
556	def name(self) -> str:
557		members_str: str = ", ".join(
558			[self._stringify(k, v) for k, v in self.__dict__.items() if k != "_type_"],
559		)
560		output: str = f"{type(self).__name__}({members_str})"
561		if "." in output and output.index("(") > output.index("."):
562			return "".join(output.split(".")[1:])
563		else:
564			return output
565
566	def __str__(self) -> str:
567		return self.name
568
569	# TYPING: type hints for `__init_subclass__`?
570	def __init_subclass__(cls, **kwargs):  # noqa: ANN204
571		"""Hack: dataclass hashes don't include the class itself in the hash function inputs.
572
573		This causes dataclasses with identical fields but different types to hash identically.
574		This hack circumvents this by adding a slightly hidden field to every subclass with a value of `repr(cls)`.
575		To maintain compatibility with `all_instances`, the static type of the new field can only have 1 possible value.
576		So we type it as a singleton `Literal` type.
577		muutils 0.6.1 doesn't support `Literal` type validation, so `assert_type=False`.
578		Ignore Pylance complaining about the arg to `Literal` being an expression.
579		"""
580		super().__init_subclass__(**kwargs)
581		cls._type_ = serializable_field(
582			init=True,
583			repr=False,
584			default=repr(cls),
585			assert_type=False,
586		)
587		cls.__annotations__["_type_"] = Literal[repr(cls)]
588
589	def __hash__(self) -> int:
590		"Stable hash to identify unique `MazeTokenizerModular` instances. uses name"
591		return int.from_bytes(
592			hashlib.blake2b(self.name.encode("utf-8")).digest(),
593			byteorder="big",
594		)
595
596	@classmethod
597	def _level_one_subclass(cls) -> type["_TokenizerElement"]:
598		"""Returns the immediate subclass of `_TokenizerElement` of which `cls` is an instance."""
599		return (
600			set(cls.__mro__).intersection(set(_TokenizerElement.__subclasses__())).pop()
601		)
602
603	def tokenizer_elements(self, deep: bool = True) -> list["_TokenizerElement"]:
604		"""Returns a list of all `_TokenizerElement` instances contained in the subtree.
605
606		Currently only detects `_TokenizerElement` instances which are either direct attributes of another instance or
607		which sit inside a `tuple` without further nesting.
608
609		# Parameters
610		- `deep: bool`: Whether to return elements nested arbitrarily deeply or just a single layer.
611		"""
612		if not any(type(el) == tuple for el in self.__dict__.values()):  # noqa: E721
613			return list(
614				flatten(
615					[
616						[el, *el.tokenizer_elements()]
617						for el in self.__dict__.values()
618						if isinstance(el, _TokenizerElement)
619					],
620				)
621				if deep
622				else filter(
623					lambda x: isinstance(x, _TokenizerElement),
624					self.__dict__.values(),
625				),
626			)
627		else:
628			non_tuple_elems: list[_TokenizerElement] = list(
629				flatten(
630					[
631						[el, *el.tokenizer_elements()]
632						for el in self.__dict__.values()
633						if isinstance(el, _TokenizerElement)
634					]
635					if deep
636					else filter(
637						lambda x: isinstance(x, _TokenizerElement),
638						self.__dict__.values(),
639					),
640				),
641			)
642			tuple_elems: list[_TokenizerElement] = list(
643				flatten(
644					[
645						(
646							[
647								[tup_el, *tup_el.tokenizer_elements()]
648								for tup_el in el
649								if isinstance(tup_el, _TokenizerElement)
650							]
651							if deep
652							else filter(lambda x: isinstance(x, _TokenizerElement), el)
653						)
654						for el in self.__dict__.values()
655						if isinstance(el, tuple)
656					],
657				),
658			)
659			non_tuple_elems.extend(tuple_elems)
660			return non_tuple_elems
661
662	def tokenizer_element_tree(self, depth: int = 0, abstract: bool = False) -> str:
663		"""Returns a string representation of the tree of tokenizer elements contained in `self`.
664
665		# Parameters
666		- `depth: int`: Current depth in the tree. Used internally for recursion, no need to specify.
667		- `abstract: bool`: Whether to print the name of the abstract base class or the concrete class for each `_TokenizerElement` instance.
668		"""
669		name: str = "\t" * depth + (
670			type(self).__name__
671			if not abstract
672			else type(self)._level_one_subclass().__name__
673		)
674		return (
675			name
676			+ "\n"
677			+ "".join(
678				el.tokenizer_element_tree(depth + 1, abstract)
679				for el in self.tokenizer_elements(deep=False)
680			)
681		)
682
683	def tokenizer_element_dict(self) -> dict:
684		"""Returns a dictionary representation of the tree of tokenizer elements contained in `self`."""
685		return {
686			type(self).__name__: {
687				key: (
688					val.tokenizer_element_dict()
689					if isinstance(val, _TokenizerElement)
690					else (
691						val
692						if not isinstance(val, tuple)
693						else [
694							(
695								el.tokenizer_element_dict()
696								if isinstance(el, _TokenizerElement)
697								else el
698							)
699							for el in val
700						]
701					)
702				)
703				for key, val in self.__dict__.items()
704				if key != "_type_"
705			},
706		}
707
708	@classmethod
709	@abc.abstractmethod
710	def attribute_key(cls) -> str:
711		"""Returns the binding used in `MazeTokenizerModular` for that type of `_TokenizerElement`."""
712		raise NotImplementedError
713
714	def to_tokens(self, *args, **kwargs) -> list[str]:
715		"""Converts a maze element into a list of tokens.
716
717		Not all `_TokenizerElement` subclasses produce tokens, so this is not an abstract method.
718		Those subclasses which do produce tokens should override this method.
719		"""
720		raise NotImplementedError
721
722	@abc.abstractmethod
723	def is_valid(self) -> bool:
724		"""Returns if `self` contains data members capable of producing an overall valid `MazeTokenizerModular`.
725
726		Some `_TokenizerElement` instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints.
727		`is_valid` allows for more precise detection of invalid `_TokenizerElement`s beyond type hinting alone.
728		If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply `return True` for that subclass.
729
730		# Types of Invalidity
731		In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below.
732		Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:
733		- Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study.
734		E.g., `_TokenizerElement`s which are strictly worse than some alternative.
735		- Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
736		- Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
737		- Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.
738
739		# Development
740		`is_invalid` is implemented to always return `True` in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid.
741		When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.
742
743		## Nesting
744		In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call `is_valid` on nested `_TokenizerElement`s contained in the class.
745		In other words, failures of `is_valid` need not bubble up to the top of the nested `_TokenizerElement` tree.
746		`MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid` calls `is_valid` on each of its `_TokenizerElement`s individually, so failure at any level will be detected.
747
748		## Types of Invalidity
749		If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments.
750		This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid `_TokenizerElement` instances.
751		"""
752		raise NotImplementedError

Superclass for tokenizer elements.

Subclasses contain modular functionality for maze tokenization.

Development

Tip

Due to the functionality of get_all_tokenizers(), _TokenizerElement subclasses may only contain fields of type utils.FiniteValued. Implementing a subclass with an int or float-typed field, for example, is not supported. In the event that adding such fields is deemed necessary, get_all_tokenizers() must be updated.

684		"""Returns a dictionary representation of the tree of tokenizer elements contained in `self`."""
685		return {
686			type(self).__name__: {
687				key: (
688					val.tokenizer_element_dict()
689					if isinstance(val, _TokenizerElement)
690					else (
691						val
692						if not isinstance(val, tuple)
693						else [
694							(
695								el.tokenizer_element_dict()
696								if isinstance(el, _TokenizerElement)
697								else el
698							)
699							for el in val
700						]
701					)
702				)
703				for key, val in self.__dict__.items()
704				if key != "_type_"
705			},
706		}

@abc.abstractmethod
def is_valid(self) -> bool:
View on GitHub 
722	@abc.abstractmethod
723	def is_valid(self) -> bool:
724		"""Returns if `self` contains data members capable of producing an overall valid `MazeTokenizerModular`.
725
726		Some `_TokenizerElement` instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints.
727		`is_valid` allows for more precise detection of invalid `_TokenizerElement`s beyond type hinting alone.
728		If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply `return True` for that subclass.
729
730		# Types of Invalidity
731		In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below.
732		Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:
733		- Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study.
734		E.g., `_TokenizerElement`s which are strictly worse than some alternative.
735		- Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
736		- Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
737		- Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.
738
739		# Development
740		`is_invalid` is implemented to always return `True` in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid.
741		When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.
742
743		## Nesting
744		In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call `is_valid` on nested `_TokenizerElement`s contained in the class.
745		In other words, failures of `is_valid` need not bubble up to the top of the nested `_TokenizerElement` tree.
746		`MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid` calls `is_valid` on each of its `_TokenizerElement`s individually, so failure at any level will be detected.
747
748		## Types of Invalidity
749		If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments.
750		This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid `_TokenizerElement` instances.
751		"""
752		raise NotImplementedError

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular.

Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

2041
2042	# Parameters
2043	- `prompt_sequencer`: Tokenizer element which assembles token regions (adjacency list, origin, target, path) into a complete prompt.
2044
2045	# Development
2046	- To ensure backwards compatibility, the default constructor must always return a tokenizer equivalent to the legacy `TokenizationMode.AOTP_UT_Uniform`.
2047	- Furthermore, the mapping reflected in `from_legacy` must also be maintained.

2056	def hash_int(self) -> int:
2057		"return integer hash using blake2b"
2058		return int.from_bytes(
2059			hashlib.blake2b(self.name.encode("utf-8")).digest(),
2060			byteorder="big",
2061		)

2067	def hash_b64(self, n_bytes: int = 8) -> str:
2068		"""filename-safe base64 encoding of the hash"""
2069		# Use modulus to ensure the integer fits within n_bytes * 8 bits
2070		hash_mod: int = self.hash_int() % (1 << (n_bytes * 8))
2071
2072		encoded = base64.b64encode(
2073			hash_mod.to_bytes(n_bytes, byteorder="big"),
2074			altchars=b"-_",
2075		).decode()
2076
2077		# Remove any padding equals signs
2078		return encoded.rstrip("=")

2134	def _has_element_singular(
2135		self,
2136		el: type[_TokenizerElement] | _TokenizerElement,
2137	) -> bool:
2138		"""Helper method for `has_element`"""
2139		self._type_check(el)
2140		if isinstance(el, type):
2141			return any(isinstance(e, el) for e in self.tokenizer_elements)
2142		else:
2143			return el in self.tokenizer_elements

2145	def has_element(
2146		self,
2147		*elements: Sequence[type[_TokenizerElement] | _TokenizerElement],
2148	) -> bool:
2149		"""Returns True if the `MazeTokenizerModular` instance contains ALL of the items specified in `elements`.
2150
2151		Querying with a partial subset of `_TokenizerElement` fields is not currently supported.
2152		To do such a query, assemble multiple calls to `has_elements`.
2153
2154		# Parameters
2155		- `elements`: Singleton or iterable of `_TokenizerElement` instances or classes.
2156		If an instance is provided, then comparison is done via instance equality.
2157		If a class is provided, then comparison isdone via `isinstance`. I.e., any instance of that class is accepted.
2158		"""
2159		if len(elements) == 1 and isinstance(elements[0], Iterable):
2160			elements = elements[0]
2161		return all(self._has_element_singular(e) for e in elements)

2164		"""Returns `True` if `self` is a valid tokenizer.
2165
2166		Evaluates the validity of all of `self.tokenizer_elements` according to each one's method.
2167		"""
2168		return all(el.is_valid() for el in self.tokenizer_elements)

2177	def is_tested_tokenizer(self, do_assert: bool = False) -> bool:
2178		"""Returns if the tokenizer is returned by `all_tokenizers.get_all_tokenizers`, the set of tested and reliable tokenizers.
2179
2180		Since evaluating `all_tokenizers.get_all_tokenizers` is expensive,
2181		instead checks for membership of `self`'s hash in `get_all_tokenizer_hashes()`.
2182
2183		if `do_assert` is `True`, raises an `AssertionError` if the tokenizer is not tested.
2184		"""
2185		all_tokenizer_hashes: Int64[np.ndarray, " n_tokenizers"] = (
2186			get_all_tokenizer_hashes()
2187		)
2188		hash_index: int = np.searchsorted(all_tokenizer_hashes, hash(self))
2189
2190		in_range: bool = hash_index < len(all_tokenizer_hashes)
2191		hashes_match: bool = all_tokenizer_hashes[hash_index] == hash(self)
2192		is_valid: bool = self.is_valid()
2193
2194		if do_assert:
2195			assert in_range, (
2196				f"{hash_index = } is invalid, must be at most {len(all_tokenizer_hashes) - 1}"
2197			)
2198			assert hashes_match, (
2199				f"{all_tokenizer_hashes[hash_index] = } != {hash(self) = }"
2200			)
2201			assert is_valid, "self.is_valid returns False"
2202			return True
2203		else:
2204			return in_range and hashes_match and is_valid

def is_tested_tokenizer(self, do_assert: bool = False) -> bool:
View on GitHub 
2177	def is_tested_tokenizer(self, do_assert: bool = False) -> bool:
2178		"""Returns if the tokenizer is returned by `all_tokenizers.get_all_tokenizers`, the set of tested and reliable tokenizers.
2179
2180		Since evaluating `all_tokenizers.get_all_tokenizers` is expensive,
2181		instead checks for membership of `self`'s hash in `get_all_tokenizer_hashes()`.
2182
2183		if `do_assert` is `True`, raises an `AssertionError` if the tokenizer is not tested.
2184		"""
2185		all_tokenizer_hashes: Int64[np.ndarray, " n_tokenizers"] = (
2186			get_all_tokenizer_hashes()
2187		)
2188		hash_index: int = np.searchsorted(all_tokenizer_hashes, hash(self))
2189
2190		in_range: bool = hash_index < len(all_tokenizer_hashes)
2191		hashes_match: bool = all_tokenizer_hashes[hash_index] == hash(self)
2192		is_valid: bool = self.is_valid()
2193
2194		if do_assert:
2195			assert in_range, (
2196				f"{hash_index = } is invalid, must be at most {len(all_tokenizer_hashes) - 1}"
2197			)
2198			assert hashes_match, (
2199				f"{all_tokenizer_hashes[hash_index] = } != {hash(self) = }"
2200			)
2201			assert is_valid, "self.is_valid returns False"
2202			return True
2203		else:
2204			return in_range and hashes_match and is_valid

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

1872		def _get_prompt_regions(
1873			self,
1874			maze: LatticeMaze,
1875			*args,
1876			**kwargs,
1877		) -> list[list[str]]:
1878			"""Gets the prompt regions of a maze in a fixed sequence.
1879
1880			This method is NOT responsible for including/excluding any prompt regions.
1881			Always return according to the API described under Returns.
1882			This implementation is expected to be suitable for most `PromptSequencer` subclasses.
1883			Subclasses may override this method if needed for special behavior.
1884
1885			# Returns
1886			- [0]: list[str] Adjacency list tokens
1887			- [1]: list[str] Origin tokens
1888			- [2]: list[str] Target tokens
1889			- [3]: list[str] Path tokens
1890
1891			# `None`-valued Args
1892			If one or more of `origin`, `target`, or `path` are `None`, that indicates that an unsolved or untargeted maze is being tokenized.
1893			To ensure unpackability in `_sequence_tokens`, these `None` values are substituted for empty iterables.
1894			"""
1895			origin: Coord | None = getattr(maze, "start_pos", None)
1896			target: list[Coord] | None = [
1897				getattr(maze, "end_pos", None),
1898			]  # TargetTokenizer requires target: Sequence[Coord]
1899
1900			return [
1901				(
1902					self.adj_list_tokenizer.to_tokens(
1903						maze,
1904						coord_tokenizer=self.coord_tokenizer,
1905					)
1906					if hasattr(self, "adj_list_tokenizer")
1907					else []
1908				),
1909				self.coord_tokenizer.to_tokens(origin) if origin is not None else [],
1910				(
1911					self.target_tokenizer.to_tokens(
1912						target,
1913						coord_tokenizer=self.coord_tokenizer,
1914					)
1915					if target[0] is not None and hasattr(self, "target_tokenizer")
1916					else []
1917				),
1918				(
1919					self.path_tokenizer.to_tokens(
1920						maze,
1921						coord_tokenizer=self.coord_tokenizer,
1922					)
1923					if hasattr(maze, "solution") and hasattr(self, "path_tokenizer")
1924					else []
1925				),

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

1101class AdjListTokenizers(__TokenizerElementNamespace):
1102	"""Namespace for `_AdjListTokenizer` subclass hierarchy used by `MazeTokenizerModular`."""

1104	key = "adj_list_tokenizer"
1105
1106	@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1107	@mark_as_unsupported(lambda self_: self_.pre is False)
1108	class _AdjListTokenizer(_TokenizerElement, abc.ABC):
1109		"""Specifies how the adjacency list is tokenized.
1110
1111		Tokenization behavior is decomposed into specification of edge subsets, groupings, and permutations.
1112		See documentation of `EdgeSubset` and `EdgeGrouping` classes for more details.
1113
1114		# Parameters
1115		- `pre`: Whether all edge groupings include a preceding delimiter token
1116		- `post`: Whether all edge groupings include a following delimiter token
1117		- `shuffle_d0`: Specifies how to sequence the edge groupings.
1118			If true, groupings are shuffled randomly. If false, groupings are sorted by the leading coord of each group.
1119		- `edge_grouping`: Specifies if/how multiple coord-coord connections are grouped together in a token subsequence called an edge grouping.
1120		- `edge_subset`: Specifies the subset of lattice edges to be tokenized.
1121		- `edge_permuter`: Specifies, in each edge tokenization, which coord either:
1122			1. Appears first in the tokenization, for `AdjListCoord`.
1123			2. Is tokenized directly as a coord, for `AdjListCardinal`.
1124			- `shuffle`: For each edge, the leading coord is selected randomly.
1125			- `all`: Each edge appears twice in the tokenization, appearing with both leading coords.
1126			- `evens`, `odds`: The leading coord is the one belonging to that coord subset. See `EdgeSubsets.ChessboardSublattice` for details.
1127		"""
1128

1177		) -> Sequence[str]:
1178			"""Tokenizes a single edge grouping."""
1179			cxn_ord: int = group_params["connection_token_ordinal"]
1180			is_conn: Bool[np.ndarray, edges] = is_connection(
1181				edges,
1182				maze.connection_list,
1183			)

1188			)
1189
1190			if group_params["grouped"]:
1191				# If grouped
1192				callable_permutation: list[int] = [1, 2] if cxn_ord == 0 else [2, 1]
1193				repeated_callables = [
1194					tokenize_callables[i] for i in callable_permutation
1195				]
1196				return flatten(
1197					[
1198						tokenize_callables[0](0),
1199						[
1200							[
1201								*[
1202									tok_callable(i)
1203									for tok_callable in repeated_callables
1204								],
1205								*(
1206									(VOCAB.ADJLIST_INTRA,)
1207									if group_params["intra"]
1208									else ()
1209								),
1210							]
1211							for i in range(edges.shape[0])
1212						],
1213					],
1214				)
1215			else:
1216				# If ungrouped
1217				callable_permutation = [0, 2]
1218				callable_permutation.insert(cxn_ord, 1)
1219				tokenize_callables = [
1220					tokenize_callables[i] for i in callable_permutation
1221				]
1222
1223				return flatten(
1224					[
1225						[
1226							[
1227								*[
1228									tok_callable(i)
1229									for tok_callable in tokenize_callables
1230								],
1231								*empty_sequence_if_attr_false(
1232									(VOCAB.ADJLIST_INTRA,),
1233									group_params,
1234									"intra",
1235								),
1236							]
1237							for i in range(edges.shape[0])
1238						],
1239					],
1240				)
1241
1242		def to_tokens(
1243			self,
1244			maze: LatticeMaze,
1245			coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer,
1246		) -> list[str]:
1247			# Get the set of edges to be tokenized
1248			edges: ConnectionArray = self.edge_subset._get_edges(maze)
1249			# Systematically permute the leading coord of each edge
1250			edges: ConnectionArray = self.edge_permuter._permute(edges)
1251			group_params: EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams = (
1252				self.edge_grouping._token_params()
1253			)
1254			# then, we need to group the edges
1255			groups: Sequence[ConnectionArray] = self.edge_grouping._group_edges(edges)
1256			# shuffle the groups if specified
1257			if self.shuffle_d0:
1258				if isinstance(groups, np.ndarray):
1259					numpy_rng.shuffle(groups, axis=0)
1260				elif isinstance(groups, list):
1261					random.shuffle(groups)
1262				else:
1263					err_msg: str = f"`groups` is an unexpected type {type(groups)}. Only types `list` and `np.ndarray` are currently supported."
1264					raise TypeError(err_msg)
1265			# Tokenize each group with optional delimiters
1266			tokens: list[str] = list(
1267				flatten(
1268					[
1269						[
1270							*empty_sequence_if_attr_false(
1271								(VOCAB.ADJLIST_PRE,),
1272								self,
1273								"pre",
1274							),
1275							*self._tokenize_edge_grouping(
1276								group,
1277								maze,
1278								coord_tokenizer,
1279								group_params,
1280							),
1281							*empty_sequence_if_attr_false(
1282								(VOCAB.ADJACENCY_ENDLINE,),
1283								self,
1284								"post",
1285							),
1286						]
1287						for group in groups
1288					],
1289				),
1290			)
1291			return tokens

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

871	@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
872	class _EdgeGrouping(_TokenizerElement, abc.ABC):
873		"""Specifies if/how multiple coord-coord connections are grouped together in a token subsequence called a edge grouping."""
874
