876		def attribute_key(cls) -> str:
877			return EdgeGroupings.key

882		@abc.abstractmethod
883		def _group_edges(self, edges: ConnectionArray) -> Sequence[ConnectionArray]:

885
886			Shuffles/sequences within each group if applicable.

890		@abc.abstractmethod
891		def _token_params(self) -> "EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams":
892			"""Returns the tok.nization hyperparameters necessary for an `AdjListTokenizer` to tokenize.
893
894			These hyperparameters are not used by `_EdgeGrouping` internally.
895			They are located in `_EdgeGrouping` rather than in `AdjListTokenizer`
896			since the hyperparameter space is a function of the `_EdgeGrouping` subclass.
897			This function resolves the `_EdgeGrouping` hyperparameter space which is non-uniform across subclasses
898			into a uniform private interface used by `AdjListTokenizer`.
899			"""
900			pass

904		"""No grouping occurs, each edge is tokenized individually.
905
906		# Parameters
907		- `connection_token_ordinal`: At which index in the edge tokenization the connector (or wall) token appears.
908		Edge tokenizations contain 3 parts: a leading coord, a connector (or wall) token, and either a second coord or cardinal direction tokenization.
909		"""

919				intra=False,
920				grouped=False,
921			)
922
923		def _group_edges(self, edges: ConnectionList) -> Sequence[ConnectionList]:
924			return np.expand_dims(edges, 1)

926	@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
927	@mark_as_unsupported(lambda self_: False)  # noqa: ARG005
928	class ByLeadingCoord(_EdgeGrouping):
929		"""All edges with the same leading coord are grouped together.
930
931		# Parameters
932		- `intra`: Whether all edge groupings include a delimiter token between individual edge representations.
933		Note that each edge representation will already always include a connector token (`VOCAB.CONNECTOR`, or possibly `)
934		- `shuffle_group`: Whether the sequence of edges within the group should be shuffled or appear in a fixed order.
935		If false, the fixed order is lexicographical by (row, col).
936		In effect, lexicographical sorting sorts edges by their cardinal direction in the sequence NORTH, WEST, EAST, SOUTH, where the directions indicate the position of the trailing coord relative to the leading coord.
937		- `connection_token_ordinal`: At which index in token sequence representing a single edge the connector (or wall) token appears.
938		Edge tokenizations contain 2 parts: a connector (or wall) token and a coord or cardinal tokenization.
939		"""
940
941		intra: bool = serializable_field(default=True)
942		shuffle_group: bool = serializable_field(default=True)
943		connection_token_ordinal: Literal[0, 1] = serializable_field(
944			default=0,
945			assert_type=False,
946		)
947
948		def _token_params(self) -> "EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams":
949			return EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams(
950				connection_token_ordinal=self.connection_token_ordinal,
951				intra=self.intra,
952				grouped=True,
953			)
954
955		def _group_edges(self, edges: ConnectionArray) -> Sequence[ConnectionArray]:
956			# Adapted from: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38013778/is-there-any-numpy-group-by-function
957			index_array: Int[np.ndarray, "sort_indices=edges"] = np.lexsort(
958				(edges[:, 1, 1], edges[:, 1, 0], edges[:, 0, 1], edges[:, 0, 0]),
959			)
960			sorted_edges: ConnectionArray = edges[index_array, ...]
961			groups: list[ConnectionArray] = np.split(
962				sorted_edges,
963				np.unique(sorted_edges[:, 0, :], return_index=True, axis=0)[1][1:],
964			)
965			if self.shuffle_group:
966				[numpy_rng.shuffle(g, axis=0) for g in groups]
967			return groups

938		Edge tokenizations contain 2 parts: a connector (or wall) token and a coord or cardinal tokenization.
939		"""
940
941		intra: bool = serializable_field(default=True)
942		shuffle_group: bool = serializable_field(default=True)
943		connection_token_ordinal: Literal[0, 1] = serializable_field(
944			default=0,
945			assert_type=False,
946		)
947
948		def _token_params(self) -> "EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams":
949			return EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams(
950				connection_token_ordinal=self.connection_token_ordinal,
951				intra=self.intra,
952				grouped=True,
953			)
954
955		def _group_edges(self, edges: ConnectionArray) -> Sequence[ConnectionArray]:
956			# Adapted from: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38013778/is-there-any-numpy-group-by-function
957			index_array: Int[np.ndarray, "sort_indices=edges"] = np.lexsort(
958				(edges[:, 1, 1], edges[:, 1, 0], edges[:, 0, 1], edges[:, 0, 0]),
959			)
960			sorted_edges: ConnectionArray = edges[index_array, ...]
961			groups: list[ConnectionArray] = np.split(
962				sorted_edges,
963				np.unique(sorted_edges[:, 0, :], return_index=True, axis=0)[1][1:],
964			)
965			if self.shuffle_group:
966				[numpy_rng.shuffle(g, axis=0) for g in groups]
967			return groups

All edges with the same leading coord are grouped together.

Parameters

  • intra: Whether all edge groupings include a delimiter token between individual edge representations. Note that each edge representation will already always include a connector token (VOCAB.CONNECTOR, or possibly `)
  • shuffle_group: Whether the sequence of edges within the group should be shuffled or appear in a fixed order. If false, the fixed order is lexicographical by (row, col). In effect, lexicographical sorting sorts edges by their cardinal direction in the sequence NORTH, WEST, EAST, SOUTH, where the directions indicate the position of the trailing coord relative to the leading coord.
  • connection_token_ordinal: At which index in token sequence representing a single edge the connector (or wall) token appears. Edge tokenizations contain 2 parts: a connector (or wall) token and a coord or cardinal tokenization.

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular.

Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

def validate_fields_types( self: muutils.json_serialize.serializable_dataclass.SerializableDataclass, on_typecheck_error: muutils.errormode.ErrorMode = ErrorMode.Except) -> bool:
View on GitHub 
283def SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types(
284    self: SerializableDataclass,
285    on_typecheck_error: ErrorMode = _DEFAULT_ON_TYPECHECK_ERROR,
286) -> bool:
287    """validate the types of all the fields on a `SerializableDataclass`. calls `SerializableDataclass__validate_field_type` for each field"""
288    return all(
289        SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
290            self, on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error
291        ).values()
292    )

813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

def is_valid(self) -> bool:
View on GitHub 
1408		def is_valid(self) -> bool:  # noqa: D102
1409			# No invalid instances possible within data member type hint bounds
1410			return True

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular.

Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular.

Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )

def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular.

Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

1633			d: int = end_index - start_index
1634			return [getattr(VOCAB, f"I_{d:03}")]
1635

1639	This type exists mostly just for the clarity and convenience of `_PathTokenizer` code.
1640	"""

1645		| tuple[_StepTokenizer, _StepTokenizer, _StepTokenizer, _StepTokenizer]

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

1580	@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1581	class Relative(_StepTokenizer):
1582		"""Tokenizes a solution step using relative first-person directions (right, left, forward, etc.).
1583
1584		To simplify the indeterminacy, at the start of a solution the "agent" solving the maze is assumed to be facing NORTH.
1585		Similarly to `Cardinal`, the direction is that of the step from the starting position.
1586		"""

1594			**kwargs,
1595		) -> list[str]:
1596			if start_index == 0:
1597				start = maze.solution[0]
1598				previous = start + np.array([1, 0])
1599				return [
1600					get_relative_direction(
1601						np.concatenate(
1602							(
1603								np.expand_dims(previous, 0),
1604								maze.solution[start_index : start_index + 2],
1605							),
1606							axis=0,
1607						),
1608					),
1609				]
1610			return [
1611				get_relative_direction(
1612					maze.solution[start_index - 1 : start_index + 2],
1613				),
1614			]

761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
777        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
778        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
779            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
780            if isinstance(data, cls):
781                return data
782
783            assert isinstance(
784                data, typing.Mapping
785            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
786
787            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
788
789            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
790            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
791
792            # iterate over the fields of the class
793            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
794                # check if the field is a SerializableField
795                assert isinstance(
796                    field, SerializableField
797                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
798
799                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
800                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
801                    # get the value, we will be processing it
802                    value: Any = data[field.name]
803
804                    # get the type hint for the field
805                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
806
807                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
808                    if field.deserialize_fn:
809                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
810                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
811                    elif field.loading_fn:
812                        # if it has a loading function, use that
813                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
814                    elif (
815                        field_type_hint is not None
816                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
817                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
818                    ):
819                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
820                        if isinstance(value, dict):
821                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
822                        else:
823                            raise FieldLoadingError(
824                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
825                            )
826                    else:
827                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
828                        pass
829
830                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
831                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
832
833            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
834            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
835
836            # validate the types of the fields if needed
837            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
838                fields_valid: dict[str, bool] = (
839                    SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(
840                        output,
841                        on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error,
842                    )
843                )
844
845                # if there are any fields that are not valid, raise an error
846                if not all(fields_valid.values()):
847                    msg: str = (
848                        f"Type mismatch in fields of {cls.__name__}:\n"
849                        + "\n".join(
850                            [
851                                f"{k}:\texpected {cls_type_hints[k] = }, but got value {getattr(output, k) = }, {type(getattr(output, k)) = }"
852                                for k, v in fields_valid.items()
853                                if not v
854                            ]
855                        )
856                    )
857
858                    on_typecheck_mismatch.process(
859                        msg, except_cls=FieldTypeMismatchError
860                    )
861
862            # return the new instance
863            return output

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
714        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
715            result: dict[str, Any] = {
716                _FORMAT_KEY: f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
717            }
718            # for each field in the class
719            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
720                # need it to be our special SerializableField
721                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
722                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
723                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
724                        f"but a {type(field)} "
725                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
726                    )
727
728                # try to save it
729                if field.serialize:
730                    try:
731                        # get the val
732                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
733                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
734                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
735                            value = value.serialize()
736                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
737                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
738                            value = value.serialize()
739                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
740                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
741                        elif field.serialization_fn:
742                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
743
744                        # store the value in the result
745                        result[field.name] = value
746                    except Exception as e:
747                        raise FieldSerializationError(
748                            "\n".join(
749                                [
750                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
751                                    f"{field = }",
752                                    f"{value = }",
753                                    f"{self = }",
754                                ]
755                            )
756                        ) from e
757
758            # store each property if we can get it
759            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
760                if hasattr(cls, prop):
761                    value = getattr(self, prop)
762                    result[prop] = value
763                else:
764                    raise AttributeError(
765                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
766                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
767                        + f"\n{self = }"
768                    )
769
770            return result

1649class PathTokenizers(__TokenizerElementNamespace):
1650	"""Namespace for `_PathTokenizer` subclass hierarchy used by `MazeTokenizerModular`."""

1652	key = "path_tokenizer"
1653
1654	@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1655	class _PathTokenizer(_TokenizerElement, abc.ABC):
1656		"""Superclass of tokenizers for maze solution paths."""
1657
1658		@abc.abstractmethod
1659		def to_tokens(
1660			self,
1661			maze: SolvedMaze,
1662			coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer,
1663		) -> list[str]:
1664			"""Returns tokens representing the solution path."""
1665			pass
1666
1667		@classmethod
1668		def attribute_key(cls) -> str:
1669			return PathTokenizers.key
1670
1671	@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1672	class StepSequence(_PathTokenizer, abc.ABC):
1673		"""Any `PathTokenizer` where the tokenization may be assembled from token subsequences, each of which represents a step along the path.
1674
1675		Allows for a sequence of leading and trailing tokens which don't fit the step pattern.
1676
1677		# Parameters
1678		- `step_size`: Selects the size of a single step in the sequence
1679		- `step_tokenizers`: Selects the combination and permutation of tokens
1680		- `pre`: Whether all steps include an integral preceding delimiter token
1681		- `intra`: Whether all steps include a delimiter token after each individual `_StepTokenizer` tokenization.
1682		- `post`: Whether all steps include an integral following delimiter token
1683		"""
1684
1685		step_size: StepSizes._StepSize = serializable_field(
1686			default=StepSizes.Singles(),
1687			loading_fn=lambda x: _load_tokenizer_element(x, StepSizes),
1688		)
1689		step_tokenizers: StepTokenizers.StepTokenizerPermutation = serializable_field(
1690			default=(StepTokenizers.Coord(),),
1691			serialization_fn=lambda x: [y.serialize() for y in x],
1692			loading_fn=lambda x: tuple(x[StepTokenizers.key]),
1693		)
1694		pre: bool = serializable_field(default=False)
1695		intra: bool = serializable_field(default=False)
1696		post: bool = serializable_field(default=False)
1697
1698		# inherit docstring
1699		def to_tokens(  # noqa: D102
1700			self,
1701			maze: SolvedMaze,
1702			coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer,
1703		) -> list[str]:
1704			return [
1705				*self._leading_tokens(maze, coord_tokenizer),
1706				*flatten(
1707					[
1708						self._single_step_tokens(maze, start, end, coord_tokenizer)
1709						for start, end in self.step_size.step_start_end_indices(maze)
1710					],
1711				),
1712				*self._trailing_tokens(maze, coord_tokenizer),
1713			]
1714
1715		def _single_step_tokens(
1716			self,
1717			maze: SolvedMaze,
1718			i: int,
1719			j: int,
1720			coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer,
1721		) -> list[str]:
1722			"""Returns the token sequence representing a single step along the path."""
1723			step_rep_tokens: list[list[str]] = [
1724				step_tokenizer.to_tokens(maze, i, j, coord_tokenizer=coord_tokenizer)
1725				for step_tokenizer in self.step_tokenizers
1726			]
1727			if self.intra:
1728				step_rep_tokens_and_intra: list[str] = [None] * (
1729					len(step_rep_tokens) * 2
1730				)
1731				step_rep_tokens_and_intra[::2] = step_rep_tokens
1732				step_rep_tokens_and_intra[1::2] = [VOCAB.PATH_INTRA] * len(
1733					step_rep_tokens,
1734				)
1735				step_rep_tokens = list(flatten(step_rep_tokens_and_intra))
1736			all_tokens: list[str] = [
1737				*empty_sequence_if_attr_false((VOCAB.PATH_PRE,), self, "pre"),
1738				*flatten(step_rep_tokens),
1739				*empty_sequence_if_attr_false((VOCAB.PATH_POST,), self, "post"),
1740			]
1741			return all_tokens
1742
1743		def _leading_tokens(
1744			self,
1745			maze: SolvedMaze,
1746			coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer,
1747		) -> list[str]:
1748			"""Returns tokens preceding those from the sequence from `_single_step_tokens`.
1749
1750			Since the for loop in `to_tokens` iterates `len(path)-1` times, a fencepost problem exists with `StepTokenizers.Coord`.
1751			<PATH_START> should NOT be included.
1752			"""
1753			if StepTokenizers.Coord() in self.step_tokenizers:
1754				return [
1755					*empty_sequence_if_attr_false((VOCAB.PATH_PRE,), self, "pre"),
1756					*coord_tokenizer.to_tokens(maze.solution[0, ...]),
1757					*empty_sequence_if_attr_false((VOCAB.PATH_INTRA,), self, "intra"),
1758				]
1759			return []
1760
1761		def _trailing_tokens(
1762			self,
1763			c: Coord,
1764			coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer,
1765		) -> list[str]:
1766			"""Returns tokens following those from the sequence from `_single_step_tokens`.
1767
1768			<PATH_END> should NOT be included.
1769			"""
1770			return []
1771
1772		# inherits docstring
1773		def is_valid(self) -> bool:  # noqa: D102
1774			if len(set(self.step_tokenizers)) != len(self.step_tokenizers):
1775				# Uninteresting: repeated elements are not useful
1776				return False
1777
1778			# we do noqa for the comment if false
1779			if len(self.step_tokenizers) == 1 and isinstance(  # noqa: SIM103
1780				self.step_tokenizers[0],
1781				StepTokenizers.Distance,
1782			):
1783				# Untrainable: `Distance` alone cannot encode a path. >=1 `StepTokenizer` which indicates direction/location is required.
1784				return False
1785			else:
1786				return True

1737				*empty_sequence_if_attr_false((VOCAB.PATH_PRE,), self, "pre"),
1738				*flatten(step_rep_tokens),
1739				*empty_sequence_if_attr_false((VOCAB.PATH_POST,), self, "post"),
1740			]
1741			return all_tokens

1748			"""Returns tokens preceding those from the sequence from `_single_step_tokens`.
1749
1750			Since the for loop in `to_tokens` iterates `len(path)-1` times, a fencepost problem exists with `StepTokenizers.Coord`.
1751			<PATH_START> should NOT be included.
1752			"""
